
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `dc` yek abzar riyazi (calculator) dar khat-e farman (command line) ast. Ba estefade az notation-e postfix (RPN - Reverse Polish Notation), shoma mitavanid amaliyat-e hesab-o-ketab ra anjam dahid. Yani aval adad-ha ra vared mikonid va ba'd amalgargar (operator) ra.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹  `dc -e 'expression'` --> 💻 Ejraye yek expression riyazi dar khat-e farman.
    🔹  `dc -f filename` --> 📑  Ejraye dastoorat az yek file.

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ dc
    1
    2
    +
    p
    q

    🔹 Dar in mesal, aval adad-ha (1 va 2) vared mishavand, sepas amalgargar-e jam (+). Dastoor `p` natije ra chap mikonad (3), va `q` az `dc` kharej mishavad.

    $ dc -e '2 3 + p'
    5

    🔹 Dar in mesal, yek expression ba notation-e postfix ejra mishavad va natije chap mishavad.

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ dc -e '10 2 / p'

    🔹 Natije-ye taghsim-e 10 bar 2 chap mishavad (5).

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `dc` command is a command-line calculator utility. It uses postfix notation (RPN - Reverse Polish Notation), allowing you to perform arithmetic operations. This means you enter the numbers first, followed by the operator.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `dc -e 'expression'` --> 💻 Execute a mathematical expression directly from the command line.
    🔹 `dc -f filename` --> 📑 Execute commands from a file.

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ dc
    1
    2
    +
    p
    q

    🔹 In this example, the numbers (1 and 2) are entered first, followed by the addition operator (+). The `p` command prints the result (3), and `q` exits `dc`.

    $ dc -e '2 3 + p'
    5

    🔹 In this example, an expression in postfix notation is executed, and the result is printed.

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ dc -e '10 2 / p'

    🔹 The result of dividing 10 by 2 is printed (5).
